content.description: Start on a less than vertical face and pull onto the rock using good feet, but barely-there hands.  High feet and body tension needed to move upwards.  Stay more right, the rock is better.  slap up to the horizontal break and add some funk to get established under the black streak water chute.  Fun stemming past 1 bolt through the chute leads to a 2-bolt anchor.
content.protection: 1 bolt.  No pro through the hard slab beginning.  If you had a pad you'd have no issues, but a busted ankle is a real possibility if not.
content.location: Lower tier of CF.  Just right of the middle of the wall and 1 route right of the thin seam of Fabulous Fables.  Look for a black water streaked chute with a bolt in it.

content.description: This is a nice crack route at the grade. The crack pinches off at the top, so you might not be getting those bomber pieces in the last ten feet. Wide crack start with face holds, then jam straight up, using pockets in the upper half. Ten feet from the top, the crack is no more and you have to face climb the rest of the way. Meticulous face climbing will get you there!
content.protection: Assortment of cams from 1/2" up to #3 Camalot. The last good hole for pro is #1 Camalot size. Bring a #3.5 and #4 Camalot for belay pro in crack running left of the top.
content.location: Crack system running up the wall just right of King Of Pain face. Just left-center of the lower CFE tier. A right-arching crack (Banana Crack) starts at the same place, but Two Cams goes straight up.

content.description: There's no way I can imagine this hasn't been climbed as it's close proximity to the main crag. However, after looking through all available guidebooks and maps and even a couple of messages to the older local trad climbers, I got nothing. So a first known ascent it is.Some good jams and nice layback movements will carry you up this seam.
content.protection: a couple 2s and a 1, sling the top to clean .. you can walk off the back

content.description: Cactus Flower East is a low-slung wall of cracks and face climbs located to the north and a little east of the main Peak area. There are a number of routes here on crystalline desert granite. The classic testpiece of the area is the ultra-thin King of Pain.There are several sets of anchors at the top of these routes and there is a side trail to the far right of the rock faces making this a Top Rope area as well as Trad.There are two distinct tiers here, you can scramble up the top of the lower tier from the left on easy 3rd class or you can follow a trail along the bottom of the cliff, and around and up the right hand side to the right end.
